      "title": "Indian Banks: Only RBI can Issue Orders, UIDAI is an External Agency",
      "country": "IN",
      "crawl_date": "2017-10-24T01:56:12Z",
      "url": "https://techgig.com/tech-news/editors-pick/Indian-Banks-Only-RBI-can-Issue-Orders-UIDAI-is-an-External-Agency-135336",
      "host": "techgig.com",
      "text": "Continue reading \nRajat Kabade \nThe Indian Bank's Association (IBA) has written a letter to the government questioning UIDAI's authority in issuing orders to the banks. UIDAI has recently started forcing banks to open enrollment and updating centers. \nThe letter clearly states that only the Reserve Bank of India (RBI) can issue directives to the banks under the Banking Regulation Act. Unique Identification Authority of India (UIDAI) is a nodal body that issues Aadhaar identification number. The Aadhaar-issuing body has recently started complaining about cooperation from banks. \nUIDAI had asked private as well as public sector banks to open Aadhaar enrollment and updating facility within bank's premises in July. The nodal body had asked the banks to open at least one-tenth of their branches by the end of August. Later UIDAI extended the deadline by a month and said it will impose Rs 20,000 fine per uncovered branch after September 30th. \nAadhaar-issuing body later published another directive on October 7th forcing all the banks to become Aadhaar registrar and enrollment agency. The directive signed by UIDAI chief, Ajay Bhushan Pandey further stated that banks will no longer be able to engage private agencies for Aadhaar enrollment of their customers. The circular was sent to all the 15,300 targeted branches by the UIDAI. \nThe Indian Bank Association's letter to the government highlights all the issues associated with banks creating Aadhaar facility within their branches. The enrollment and registration of Aadhaar is not the primary function of banks. The external authority demanding the banks to include Aadhaar enrollment as part of banking activities is not approved by the RBI yet. \nReserve Bank of India has not published any official circular regarding mandatory linking of Aadhaar number with bank accounts. The banks are demanding the freedom to design their own strategy for Aadhaar enrollment considering the available workforce.",
