      "text": "New Chinese film 'Road to the Sky' tells story of WWII China-Myanmar supply lifeline nicknamed the 'Second Great Wall' By Wei Xi Source:Global Times   17:18:39 New Chinese film tells story of WWII China-Myanmar supply lifeline Promotional material for Road to the Sky Photo: Courtesy of TiHE Communications While for most Chinese today, the Burma Road is nothing more than a name in history books, but for Chinese mainland filmmaker Wang Yi, bringing the history of this vital World War II supply line that connected Kunming in China's Yunnan Province to Lashio in Myanmar (then known as Burma) onto the big screen has been a rewarding endeavor that has taken up the past three years of his life. Despite the fact that his historical feature Road to the Sky has screened at 46 international film festivals abroad, grabbing 23 awards in the process, Wang said that he still feels fortunate that the film will be releasing nationwide in China on Tuesday. Recreating history \"I have TiHE Communication to thank for the release,\" Wang told the Global Times on the phone. Based on the real life story of how people from China and Myanmar worked together to build a 1,154-kilometer-military supply road in just eight months in 1937, Road to the Sky narrows its focus to two villages in South China's Yunnan Province, showing how villagers progress from begrudging reluctance to dedicating themselves entirely to the project. To add to the realism, Oliver Lucas, the film's US producer, even went so far as to purchase some original footage showing construction of the road, shot by a US journalist during World War II, from the US Library of Congress so it could be used in the film. On Saturday, a special prescreening of Road to the Sky was held at the MOMA Broadway Cinema in Beijing. Early reactions from the event have been overwhelmingly positive. \"What impressed me the most is how the film restored history,\" Zu Ge, a primary school teacher, told the Global Times after the prescreening. She explained that while she knew that the film would take some artistic liberties with the source material, she was impressed how real the story felt. \"I learned about this part of history in school. This film brought back those memories and gave me a better understanding of it all.\"Stating that he felt Road to the Sky is a good option for a family film for primary school children and above, Liu Yonghe, a parenting education advocate, said that \"the film provides some very good topics for parents and children to talk about: The experiences that those before us went through, and how that led to the lives we live today, as well as what kind of nation we want to build in the future.\" \"The story in Road to the Sky actually happened. I was only recovering the past,\" Wang explained.Wang pointed out that one major flaw in Chinese films today is that they are often \"unconvincing.\" \"[Though many] US films are fictional stories, they are real in spirit and so are able to convince people that what they are watching is what happened,\" he said. Wang admitted, however, that the less than 10 million yuan ($1.5 million) production is still not perfect and that there were many things he wished he could have done better, such as the film's lighting, music and dialogue. Promotional material for Road to the Sky Photo: Courtesy of TiHE Communications Making room Speaking about why he decided to support the film, Road to the Sky producer He Qin explained that he was inspired by how difficult the Burma Road project was, as it was seen as something of an impossible mission. \"The then Chinese government had asked its UK and US allies for help and was told that it would take six years using modern machinery to build such a road. However, 200,000 villagers, including the elderly, women and children, in Southwest China accomplished this task without advanced technology in just eight months,\" he said, going on to explain that this is why the road is also known as the \"Second Great Wall.\" \"It's estimated that every seven out of the 10 bullets used in major battles in China came from this supply line.\"The importance of the Burma Road is tied to the fact that it was the only land supply line China had during World War II. After the Japanese invaded China in 1937, all the major transportation lines the country had with the outside world were destroyed by the invaders. Though there have been a few other films and TV dramas about the Burma Road made in recent years, such as the seven-episode China Central TV documentary and the 2015 32-episode TV drama Twenty-four Turns , very few works have managed to make a lasting impression on general audiences.Having already traveled to 16 countries and regions for 20 showings of the film, He said that the success of films such as Road to the Sky overseas is a sign that Chinese culture is becoming more accepted. He added that now that China has been increasing its number of screens, he hopes the market make more room for smaller budget films that don't rely on star power to attract audiences. Newspaper headline: ‘Road to the Sky’ Posted in:",
