      "host": "dailymessenger.com.pk",
      "text": "Shia organizations hunger strike enters sixth day By 97 \nSJA Jafri KARACHI: The hunger strike camps continued on the sixth consecutive day in Karachi as well as throughout the country as dozens of prominent Shia and Sunni scholars, political and religious heads and people of different walk of life visited and joined strikers for immediate release of abducted, missing and kidnapped shia people nationwide. \nAccording to Messenger’s surveys thousands of Shia Muslims are gathered at various hunger strike camps arranged by the All Pakistan Shia Action Committee (APSAC), Majlis-e-Wehdatul Muslimeen (MWM) and Shia Ulema Council (SUC) while dozens of Shia Matami Organizations are also participating and supporting hunger strike camps. A large number of youngsters, old age citizens and children including the families of victims and missing persons were found at different hunger strike camps at Incholi, Rizvia, Malir, Sadaat Colony, Abbas Town and many other places of the city where protesters were demanding for immediate release of their loved ones. A movement for the safe recovery of missing Shia persons was announced a couple of weeks ago in Karachi, with leaders and members of the Shia community presenting them for voluntary arrest to force the government to take action on the issue. The ‘Fill the Jail Movement’ has been initiated in protest against the forced disappearances of hundreds of Shia persons, community leaders said. The leaders have vowed to present themselves for arrest every Friday till those missing are safely recovered. The movement, which began after a demonstration against forced disappearances, is expected to spread to other areas of the country. At least 150 Shia persons have been picked up in the country over the course of three years. MWM Deputy Speaker General Hasan Zafar Naqvi had claimed that “picking up young people from their homes and holding them captive by LEAs is a violation of human rights.” Leaders and workers of different Shia parties are participating in the protest in large numbers. SHARE",
